{"title_page": "List of Category 1 Australian region tropical cyclones", "text_new": "Category 1 is the lowest classification on the [[Australian tropical cyclone intensity scale]] used to classify tropical cyclones, that have 10-minute sustained winds of {{convert|33\u201347|kn|km/h mph}}. {{As of|2020}} tropical cyclones have peaked as Category 1 tropical cyclones in the South Pacific tropical cyclone basin, which is denoted as the waters surrounding Australia to the south of the equator, between 90\u00b0E and 160\u00b0E. The earliest tropical cyclone to be classified as a Category 1 tropical cyclone was Carmen. The latest was Harold which was classified as a Category 1 tropical cyclone as it moved through the Solomon Sea. \n\n==Background==\nThe [[Australian region tropical cyclone|Australian region tropical cyclone basin]] is located to the south of the [[Equator]] between [[90\u00b0E]] and [[160\u00b0E]].{{RA V Tropical cyclone operational plan}} The basin is officially monitored by the Australian [[Bureau of Meteorology]], Papua New Guinea's National Weather Service as well as Indonesia's [[Badan Meteorologi Klimatologi dan Geofisika]]. Other meteorological services such as the [[Fiji Meteorological Service]], the New Zealand [[MetService]], [[Meteo France]] as well as the United States [[Joint Typhoon Warning Center]] also monitor the basin.<ref name=\"SPAC TCOP\"/> Within the basin a Category 1 tropical cyclone is a [[tropical cyclone]] that has 10-minute mean maximum sustained wind speeds of {{convert|33\u201347|kn|km/h mph}} on the [[Australian tropical cyclone intensity scale]].<ref name=\"SPAC TCOP\"/><ref name=\"TC Procedures\">{{Cite report|url=http://www.met.gov.fj/TC_Procedures.pdf |title=2017/2018 Tropical Cyclone Season Summary of Alerts and Warnings Procedures for Fiji|publisher=Fiji Meteorological Service |publication-date=October 23, 2017 |pages=3 & 11|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/78dlW7gal|archivedate=May 25, 2019}}</ref> A named storm could also be classified as a Category 1 tropical cyclone if it is estimated, to have 1-minute mean maximum sustained wind speeds of between {{convert|64\u201382|kn|km/h mph}} on the [[Saffir-Simpson hurricane wind scale]].<ref name=\"SPAC TCOP\"/><ref name=\"SSHWS\">{{cite report|url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/pdf/sshws.pdf|publisher=United States National Hurricane Center|author1=Schott, Timothy|author2=Landsea, Christopher|author3=Hafele, Gene|author4=Lorens, Jeffrey|author5=Taylor, Arthur|author6=Thrum, Harvey|author7=Ward, Bill|author8=Willis, Mark|author9=Zaleski, Walt|date=January 2, 2019|accessdate=June 4, 2019|title=The Saffir-Simpson Hurricane Wind Scale}}</ref> However, this scale is not offically used in the Australian, however, various agencies including NASA also use it to compare tropical cyclones.<ref name=\"SPAC TCOP\"/> A Category 1 tropical cyclone is expected to cause some damage, if it significantly impacts land at or near its peak intensity.<ref name=\"TC Procedures\"/><ref name=\"SSHWS\"/>\n\n==Systems==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Name\n! Dates as a<br/>Category 1 \n! Duration\n! Sustained<br/>wind speeds\n! Pressure\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Land areas affected\n! Damage<br/>(USD)\n! Deaths\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Refs\n|-\n| [[Cyclone Dora|Dora]] || {{Sort|19710210|10&nbsp;\u2013 17 February 1971}} || {{Sort|144|6&nbsp;days}} || {{Sort|075|75&nbsp;km/h (45&nbsp;mph)}} || {{convert|990|hPa|inHg|abbr=on|sigfig=4|sortable=on}} || Queensland || Widespread || {{sort|0|None}} ||<ref name=\"Dora IBTRACS\">{{cite web|url={{IBTRACS url|id=1971041S20153}}|publisher=International Best Track Archive for Climate Stewardship|title=1971 Tropical Cyclone Dora (1971041S20153)|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|accessdate=25 December 2014 |title=Tropical Cyclone Dora |publisher=Australian Bureau of Meteorology |archivedate=22 March 2012 |url=http://www.bom.gov.au/cyclone/history/dora.shtml |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66MTAFldr?url=http://www.bom.gov.au/cyclone/history/dora.shtml |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[1971\u201372 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Faith|Faith]] || {{Sort|19710214|14&nbsp;\u2013 22 April 1972}} || {{Sort|192|8&nbsp;days}} || {{Sort|075|75&nbsp;km/h (45&nbsp;mph)}} || {{convert|990|hPa|inHg|abbr=on|sigfig=4|sortable=on}} || Norhtern Territory, Queensland || || ||<ref name=\"Faith IBTRACS\">{{cite web|url={{IBTRACS url|id=1972102S11140}}|publisher=International Best Track Archive for Climate Stewardship|title=1972 Tropical Cyclone Faith (1972102S11140)|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[1972\u201373 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Maud|Maud]] || {{Sort|19730129|29&nbsp;\u2013 31 January, 1973}} || {{Sort|042|1&nbsp;day 18&nbsp;hours}} || {{Sort|085|85&nbsp;km/h (50&nbsp;mph)}} || {{convert|990|hPa|inHg|abbr=on|sigfig=4|sortable=on}} || Western Australia || || ||<ref name=\"Maud IBTRACS\">{{cite web|url={{IBTRACS url|id=1973028S16123}}|publisher=International Best Track Archive for Climate Stewardship|title=1973 Tropical Cyclone Maud (1973028S16123)|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[1972\u201373 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Bella|Bella]] || {{Sort|19740323|23&nbsp;\u2013 24 March, 1973}} || {{Sort|024|1&nbsp;day}} || {{Sort|075|75&nbsp;km/h (45&nbsp;mph)}} || {{convert|998|hPa|inHg|abbr=on|sigfig=4|sortable=on}} || Northern Territory || || ||<ref name=\"Maud IBTRACS\">{{cite web|url={{IBTRACS url|id=1973028S16123}}|publisher=International Best Track Archive for Climate Stewardship|title=1973 Tropical Cyclone Maud (1973028S16123)|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[1972\u201373 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Paula|Paula]] || {{Sort|19740329|29&nbsp;\u2013 24 March, 1974}} || {{Sort|024|1&nbsp;day}} || {{Sort|075|75&nbsp;km/h (45&nbsp;mph)}} || {{convert|998|hPa|inHg|abbr=on|sigfig=4|sortable=on}} || Northern Territory || || ||<ref name=\"Paula IBTRACS\">{{cite web|u