lliam, Freda, Ima, Martin, Sally, Wini, Yali, Dovi, Nancy, Peni, Cliff (1992), Innis (1992), Nina (1992), Nisha (1993), William (1994), Evan (1996), Freda (1996), Hina (1997), June (1997), Nute (1997), Pam (1998), Ursula (1998), Veli (1998), Iris, Jo, Mona, Sose, Claudia, Jim, Vaianu, Wati, Yani, Zita, Arthur, Becky (2007), Mick (2010), Bune (2012), Lusi, Ella (2017), Oma (2019), Rita (2019), Sarai (2019), Tino (2020), Uesi (2020).\nIn addition to the 19 tropical cyclones listed above Severe Tropical Cyclone's: [[Cyclone Harry|Harry]], [[Cyclone Rewa|Rewa]] and [[Cyclone Yasi|Yasi]], all became Category 5 Severe tropical cyclones within the South Pacific Ocean, after they had moved into the [[Australian region tropical cyclone|Australian region]].<ref>{{cite web|url={{IBTRACS url|id=1989037S16164}}|title=1989 Severe Tropical Cyclone HARRY (1989037S16164)|publisher=International Best Track Archive for Climate Stewardship|accessdate=May 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url={{IBTRACS url|id=1993360S04171}}|title=1993 Severe Tropical Cyclone REWA (1993360S04171)|publisher=International Best Track Archive for Climate Stewardship|accessdate=May 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url={{IBTRACS url|id=2011028S13180}}|title=2011 Severe Tropical Cyclone YASI (2011028S13180)|publisher=International Best Track Archive for Climate Stewardship|accessdate=May 25, 2019}}</ref> [[Cyclone Anne|Severe Tropical Cyclone Anne]] was estimated to have peaked by the JTWC, with one-minute sustained wind speeds of 260&nbsp;km/h (160&nbsp;mph) for six hours during January 11, 1988.<ref name=\"Anne\">{{cite web|url={{IBTRACS url|id=1988006S05182}}|publisher=International Best Track Archive for Climate Stewardship|title=1988 Tropical Cyclone ANNE (1988006S05182)|accessdate=May 25, 2019}}</ref> This made it equivalent to a Category 5 tropical cyclone on the SSHWS, however, the FMS reported that the system had peaked with 10-minute sustained winds of 185&nbsp;km/h (115&nbsp;mph), which made it a Category 4 severe tropical cyclone on the Australian scale.<ref name=\"Anne\"/> During 2017, a study into Category 4 and 5 tropical cyclones over the South Pacific during the 1980s, was published within the [[Royal Meteorological Society]]'s [[International Journal of Climatology]].<ref name=\"Extreme\">{{cite journal|author1=Hoarau, Karl|author2=Chalonge, Ludovic|author3=Pirard, Florence |author4=Peyrusaubes, Daniel |title=Extreme tropical cyclone activities in the southern Pacific Ocean |journal=International Journal of Climatology |date=March 2018 |volume=38 |issue=3 |pages=1409\u20131420 |doi=10.1002/joc.5254}}</ref> This showed that the intensity of such tropical cyclones had been underestimated by the various warning centres during the decade.<ref name=\"Extreme\"/> In particular, they estimated that Severe Tropical Cyclone's [[Cyclone Oscar|Oscar]] and [[Cyclone Nisha-Orama|Nisha-Orama]] had 1-minute sustained winds of 285&nbsp;km/h (180&nbsp;mph), which would make them Category 5 tropical cyclones on the SSHWS.<ref name=\"Extreme\"/>\n\n==Impacts==\n\n==Records and statistics==\nWithin the official database for the region, as provided by the BoM, FMS and MetService, a total of XX tropical cyclones have been categorised as a Category 3 severe tropical cyclone. The earliest of these was Severe Tropical Cyclone Pam, which was estimated to have been a Category 5 severe tropical cyclone after a reanalysis of the data was performed by the BoM.{{BoM TC Database}} The strongest and most intense of these was Severe Tropical Cyclone Winston of the 2015-16 season, which was estimated to have 10-minute sustained wind speeds of 280&nbsp;km/h (175&nbsp;mph) and a minimum pressure of {{convert|884|hPa|inHg|sigfig=4|abbr=on}} at its peak intensity. Severe Tropical Cyclone Susan maintained its Category 5 status for around 72&nbsp;hours and was the system that maintained its Category 5 status the longest.\n -->\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=\"nb\"}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Category 1 Atlantic hurricanes]]\n*[[List of Category 1 Pacific hurricanes]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{SPAC EL's}}\n{{Tropical cyclones by intensity}}\n{{Category 1 Australian region tropical cyclones}}\n\n[[Category:Category 1 Australian region cyclones]]\n[[Category:Tropical cyclone intensity articles]]\n", "text_old": "Category 1 is the lowest classification on the [[Australian tropical cyclone intensity scale]] used to classify tropical cyclones, that have 10-minute sustained winds of {{convert|33\u201347|kn|km/h mph}}. {{As of|2020}} tropical cyclones have peaked as Category 1 tropical cyclones in the South Pacific tropical cyclone basin, which is denoted as the waters surrounding Australia to the south of the equator, between 90\u00b0E and 160\u00b0E. The earliest tropical cyclone to be classified as a Category 1 tropical cyclone was Carmen. The latest was Harold which was classified as a Category 1 tropical cyclone as it moved through the Solomon Sea. \n\n==Background==\nThe [[Australian region tropical cyclone|Australian region tropical cyclone basin]] is located to the south of the [[Equator]] between [[90\u00b0E]] and [[160\u00b0E]].{{RA V Tropical cyclone operational plan}} The basin is officially monitored by the Australian [[Bureau of Meteorology]], Papua New Guinea's National Weather Service as well as Indonesia's [[Badan Meteorologi Klimatologi dan Geofisika]]. Other meteorological services such as the [[Fiji Meteorological Service]], the New Zealand [[MetService]], [[Meteo France]] as well as the United States [[Joint Typhoon Warning Center]] also monitor the basin.<ref name=\"SPAC TCOP\"/> Within the basin a Category 1 tropical cyclone is a [[tropical cyclone]] that has 10-minute mean maximum sustained wind speeds of {{convert|33\u201347|kn|km/h mph}} on the [[Australian tropical cyclone intensity scale]].<ref name=\"SPAC TCOP\"/><ref name=\"TC Procedures\">{{Cite report|url=http://www.met.gov.fj/TC_Procedures.pdf |title=2017/2018 Tropical Cyclone Season Summary of Alerts and Warnings Procedures for Fiji|publisher=Fiji Meteorological Service |publication-date=October 23, 2017 |pages=3 & 11|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/78dlW7gal|archivedate=May 25, 2019}}</ref> A named storm could also be classified as a Category 1 tropical cyclone if it is estimated, to have 1-minute mean maximum sustained wind speeds of between {{convert|64\u201382|kn|km/h mph}} on the [[Saffir-Simpson hurricane wind scale]].<ref name=\"SPAC TCOP\"/><ref name=\"SSHWS\">{{cite report|url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/pdf/sshws.pdf|publisher=United States National Hurricane Center|author1=Schott, Timothy|author2=Landsea, Christopher|author3=Hafele, Gene|author4=Lorens, Jeffrey|author5=Taylor, Arthur|author6=Thrum, Harvey|author7=Ward, Bill|author8=Willis, Mark|author9=Zaleski, Walt|date=January 2, 2019|accessdate=June 4, 2019|title=The Saffir-Simpson Hurricane Wind Scale}}</ref> However, this scale is not offically used in the Australian, however, various agencies including NASA also use it to compare tropical cyclones.<ref name=\"SPAC TCOP\"/> A Category 1 tropical cyclone is expected to cause some damage, if it significantly impacts land at or near its peak intensity.<ref name=\"TC Procedures\"/><ref name=\"SSHWS\"/>\n\n==Systems==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Name\n! Dates as a<br/>Category 1 \n! Duration\n! Sustained<br/>wind speeds\n! Pressure\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Land areas affected\n! Damage<br/>(USD)\n! Deaths\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Refs\n|-\n| [[Cyclone Dora|Dora]] || {{Sort|19710210|10&nbsp;\u2013 17 February 1971}} || {{Sort|144|6&nbsp;days}} || {{Sort|075|75&nbsp;km/h (45&nbsp;mph)}} || {{convert|990|hPa|inHg|abbr=on|sigfig=4|sortable=on}} || Queensland || Widespread || {{sort|0|None}} ||<ref name=\"Dora IBTRACS\">{{cite web|url={{IBTRACS url|id=1971041S20153}}|publisher=International Best Track Archive for Climate Stewardship|title=1971 Tropical Cyclone Dora (1971041S20153)|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|accessdate=25 December 2014 |title=Tropical Cyclone Dora |publisher=Australian Bureau of Meteorology |archivedate=22 March 2012 |url=http://www.bom.gov.au/cyclone/history/dora.shtml |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66MTAFldr?url=http://www.bom.gov.au/cyclone/history/dora.shtml |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[1971\u201372 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Faith|Faith]] || {{Sort|19710214|14&nbsp;\u2013 22 April 1972}} || {{Sort|192|8&nbsp;days}} || {{Sort|075|75&nbsp;km/h (45&nbsp;mph)}} || {{convert|990|hPa|inHg|abbr=on|sigfig=4|sortable=on}} || Norhtern Territory, Queensland || || ||<ref name=\"Faith IBTRACS\">{{cite web|url={{IBTRACS url|id=1972102S11140}}|publisher=International Best Track Archive for Climate Stewardship|title=1972 Tropical Cyclone Faith (1972102S11140)|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[1972\u201373 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Maud|Maud]] || {{Sort|19730129|29&nbsp;\u2013 31 January, 1973}} || {{Sort|042|1&nbsp;day 18&nbsp;hours}} || {{Sort|085|85&nbsp;km/h (50&nbsp;mph)}} || {{convert|990|hPa|inHg|abbr=on|sigfig=4|sortable=on}} || Western Australia || || ||<ref name=\"Maud IBTRACS\">{{cite web|url={{IBTRACS url|id=1973028S16123}}|publisher=International Best Track Archive for Climate Stewardship|title=1973 Tropical Cyclone Maud (1973028S16123)|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[1972\u201373 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Bella|Bella]] || {{Sort|19740323|23&nbsp;\u2013 24 March, 1973}} || {{Sort|024|1&nbsp;day}} || {{Sort|075|75&nbsp;km/h (45&nbsp;mph)}} || {{convert|998|hPa|inHg|abbr=on|sigfig=4|sortable=on}} || Northern Territory || || ||<ref name=\"Maud IBTRACS\">{{cite web|url={{IBTRACS url|id=1973028S16123}}|publisher=International Best Track Archive for Climate Stewardship|title=1973 Tropical Cyclone Maud (1973028S16123)|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[1972\u201373 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclo