{sort|6|6}} ||\n|-\n|  [[2012\u201313 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Peta|Peta (2013)]]\n|-\n|  [[Cyclone Alessia|Alessia (2013)]]\n|-\n|  [[2013\u201314 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Edna|Edna (2014)]]\n|-\n|  [[2013\u201314 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Hadi|Hadi (2014)]]\n|-\n|  [[Cyclone Raquel|Raquel (2015)]]\n|-\n|  [[2016\u201317 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Yvette|Yvette (2017)]]\n|-\n|  [[2016\u201317 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Alfred|Alfred (2017)]]\n|-\n|  [[2016\u201317 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Caleb|Caleb (2017)]]\n|-\n|  [[2016\u201317 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Greg|Greg (2017)]]\n|-\n|  [[2017\u201318 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Cempaka|Cempaka (2017)]]\n|-\n|  [[2017\u201318 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Irving|Irving (2018)]]\n|-\n|  [[2017\u201318 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Linda|Linda (2018)]]\n|-\n|  [[2017\u201318 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Flamboyan|Flamboyan (2018)]]\n|-\n|  [[2018\u201319 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Kenanga|Kenanga (2019)]]\n|-\n|  [[2018\u201319 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Lili|Lili (2019)]]\n|-\n| [[Cyclone Blake|Blake (2020)]]\n|-\n|  [[Cyclone Esther|Esther (2020)]]\n|-\n|  [[Cyclone Gretel|Gretel (2020)]]\n|-\n|  [[Cyclone Harold|Harold (2020)]]\n|-\n|}\n\n<!-- \n==Other systems==\n\nTropical Cyclone Raquel (2014) developed into a Category 1 tropical cyclone, as it moved out of the region and into the Australian Region.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=February 1, 2020|title=2015 Raquel (2015180S04163)|url={{IBTRACS url|id=2015180S04163}}|publisher=The International Best Track Archive for Climate Stewardship}}</ref>\n\nThe following 52 systems were estimated to have peaked by the United States [[Joint Typhoon Warning Center]], with 1-minute sustained wind speeds equivalent to a Category 1 hurricane on the SSHWS. The majority of these tropical cyclones peaked as either a Category 2 or Category 3 on the Australian scale. Peni (1980), Sina (1980), Arthur (1981), Cliff, Tahmar, Hettie, Joti, Mark, Nano, William, Freda, Ima, Martin, Sally, Wini, Yali, Dovi, Nancy, Peni, Cliff (1992), Innis (1992), Nina (1992), Nisha (1993), William (1994), Evan (1996), Freda (1996), Hina (1997), June (1997), Nute (1997), Pam (1998), Ursula (1998), Veli (1998), Iris, Jo, Mona, Sose, Claudia, Jim, Vaianu, Wati, Yani, Zita, Arthur, Becky (2007), Mick (2010), Bune (2012), Lusi, Ella (2017), Oma (2019), Rita (2019), Sarai (2019), Tino (2020), Uesi (2020).\nIn addition to the 19 tropical cyclones listed above Severe Tropical Cyclone's: [[Cyclone Harry|Harry]], [[Cyclone Rewa|Rewa]] and [[Cyclone Yasi|Yasi]], all became Category 5 Severe tropical cyclones within the South Pacific Ocean, after they had moved into the [[Australian region tropical cyclone|Australian region]].<ref>{{cite web|url={{IBTRACS url|id=1989037S16164}}|title=1989 Severe Tropical Cyclone HARRY (1989037S16164)|publisher=International Best Track Archive for Climate Stewardship|accessdate=May 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url={{IBTRACS url|id=1993360S04171}}|title=1993 Severe Tropical Cyclone REWA (1993360S04171)|publisher=International Best Track Archive for Climate Stewardship|accessdate=May 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url={{IBTRACS url|id=2011028S13180}}|title=2011 Severe Tropical Cyclone YASI (2011028S13180)|publisher=International Best Track Archive for Climate Stewardship|accessdate=May 25, 2019}}</ref> [[Cyclone Anne|Severe Tropical Cyclone Anne]] was estimated to have peaked by the JTWC, with one-minute sustained wind speeds of 260&nbsp;km/h (160&nbsp;mph) for six hours during January 11, 1988.<ref name=\"Anne\">{{cite web|url={{IBTRACS url|id=1988006S05182}}|publisher=International Best Track Archive for Climate Stewardship|title=1988 Tropical Cyclone ANNE (1988006S05182)|accessdate=May 25, 2019}}</ref> This made it equivalent to a Category 5 tropical cyclone on the SSHWS, however, the FMS reported that the system had peaked with 10-minute sustained winds of 185&nbsp;km/h (115&nbsp;mph), which made it a Category 4 severe tropical cyclone on the Australian scale.<ref name=\"Anne\"/> During 2017, a study into Category 4 and 5 tropical cyclones over the South Pacific during the 1980s, was published within the [[Royal Meteorological Society]]'s [[International Journal of Climatology]].<ref name=\"Extreme\">{{cite journal|author1=Hoarau, Karl|author2=Chalonge, Ludovic|author3=Pirard, Florence |author4=Peyrusaubes, Daniel |title=Extreme tropical cyclone activities in the southern Pacific Ocean |journal=International Journal of Climatology |date=March 2018 |volume=38 |issue=3 |pages=1409\u20131420 |doi=10.1002/joc.5254}}</ref> This showed that the intensity of such tropical cyclones had been underestimated by the various warning centres during the decade.<ref name=\"Extreme\"/> In particular, they estimated that Severe Tropical Cyclone's [[Cyclone Oscar|Oscar]] and [[Cyclone Nisha-Orama|Nisha-Orama]] had 1-minute sustained winds of 285&nbsp;km/h (180&nbsp;mph), which would make them Category 5 tropical cyclones on the SSHWS.<ref name=\"Extreme\"/>\n\n==Impacts==\n\n==Records and statistics==\nWithin the official database for the region, as provided by the BoM, FMS and MetService, a total of XX tropical cyclones have been categorised as a Category 3 severe tropical cyclone. The earliest of these was Severe Tropical Cyclone Pam, which was estimated to have been a Category 5 severe tropical cyclone after a reanalysis of the data was performed by the BoM.{{BoM TC Database}} The strongest and most intense of these was Severe Tropical Cyclone Winston of the 2015-16 season, which was estimated to have 10-minute sustained wind speeds of 280&nbsp;km/h (175&nbsp;mph) and a minimum pressure of {{convert|884|hPa|inHg|sigfig=4|abbr=on}} at its peak intensity. Severe Tropical Cyclone Susan maintained its Category 5 status for around 72&nbsp;hours and was the system that maintained its Category 5 status the longest.\n -->\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=\"nb\"}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Category 1 Atlantic hurricanes]]\n*[[List of Category 1 Pacific hurricanes]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{SPAC EL's}}\n{{Tropical cyclones by intensity}}\n{{Category 1 Australian region tropical cyclones}}\n\n[[Category:Category 1 Australian region cyclones]]\n[[Category:Tropical cyclone intensity articles]]\n", "name_user": "Quebec99", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix duplicate ref names \u2013You can help!", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Category_1_Australian_region_tropical_cyclones"}
{"title_page": "Jeanette W. Hyde", "text_new": "'''Jeanette W. Hyde''' (born 1938) is an American diplomat. She was [[Ambassadors of the United States|Ambassador of the United States]] to [[Barbados]], [[Dominica]], [[St Lucia]] from 1994 to 1998, and to [[Antigua]], [[Grenada]], [[Saint Vincent and the Grenadines|St. Vincent]], and [[St. Christopher-Nevis-Anguilla]] from 1995 to 1998, under [[Bill Clinton]].<ref name=\"history\">[https://history.state.gov/departmenthistory/people/hyde-jeanette-w U.S. Department of State]</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nJeanette W. Hyde was born in 1938.<ref name=\"history\"/> She attended [[Wake Forest University]], and received a [[B.S.]] from [[Delta State University]] in 1962.<ref name=\"American Ambassadors\">[http://www.americanambassadors.org/index.cfm?fuseaction=Members.view&memberid=116 American Ambassadors] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070103082902/http://www.americanambassadors.org/index.cfm?fuseaction=Members.view&memberid=116 |date=2007-01-03 }}</ref> She later attended the [[University of Maryland]] on their [[Iraklion, Crete]] campus, and competed graduate studies in Counseling at the [[University of North Carolina, Chapel Hill]] and the [[North Carolina State University]].<ref name=\"American Ambassadors\"/> She was teaching school for two years in [[Crete]] before going into social work and counseling with the N.C. Administrative Office of the Courts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news-prod.wcu.edu/2005/03/wallace-hyde-gift-to-western-to-endow-social-work-professorship-in-wifes-honor/|title=Wallace Hyde gift to Western to endow social work professorship in wife's honor|date=2005-03-11|website=WCU News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref>\n\nShe married the late Wallace Hyde, a [[Robbinsville, North Carolina]] native, and was a longtime Democratic Party fundraiser.<ref>[http://projects.newsobserver.com/under_the_dome/wallace_hyde_the_democrats_big_guy_dies News & Observer: Wallace Hyde, the Democrats' big guy, dies]</ref>  \n\nShe co-founded two banks in [[Raleigh, North Carolina]], Triangle Bank and North State Bank.<ref name=\"American Ambassadors\"/>\n\nShe serves on the Board of Directors of the [[North Carolina Board of Transportation]], the [[Global TransPark|North Carolina Global Transpark]], the [[North Carolina International Trade Commission]], Outward Bound of North Carolina, and the North Carolina Child Advocacy Institute.<ref name=\"American Ambassadors\"/> She also serves on the Board of Trustees of [[Wake Forest University]], [[Western Carolina University]], and American Diplomacy Journal, Inc. She previously served on the Board of The International Cabinet at the [[University of North Carolina at Wilmington]], the Triangle World Affairs Council, Methodist Home for Children, the North Carolina Community Foundation and The Eisenhower Exchange Fellowship Board.<ref name=\"American Ambassadors\"/> \n\n== Awards ==\nIn 1994, Hyde was awarded with the Outstanding Woman in Public Service Award by the YWCA Academy of Women.\n\nIn 1998, she received the Triangle World Affairs Council's Distinguished Citizen for Public Service Award and the International Visitors Council's Citizen of the World Award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news-prod.wcu.edu/2005/03/wallace-hyde-gift-to-western-to-endow-social-work-professorship-in-wifes-honor/|title=Wallace Hyde gift to Western to endow social work professorship in wife's honor|date=2005-03-11|website=WCU News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-dip}}\n{{s-bef|rows=7|before= [[G. Philip Hughes]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title = [[United States Ambassador to Barbados]]|years = 1994-1998}}\n{{s-aft|rows=7|after= [[E. William Crotty]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title= [[United States Ambassador to Dominica]]| years  = 1994-1998}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States Ambassador to Saint Lucia]]| years  = 1994-1998}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title= [[United States Ambassador to Saint Vincent and the Grenadines]] | years  = 1994-1998}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title= [[United States Ambassador to Antigua and Barbuda]]| years  = 1995-1998}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States Ambassador to Grenada]]| years = 1995-1998}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title= [[United States Ambassador to Saint Kitts and Nevis]]| years  =  1995-1998}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hyde, Jeanette W.}}\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Wake Forest University alumni]]\n[[Category:Delta State University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Maryland, College Park alumni]]\n[[Category:University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill alumni]]\n[[Category:North Carolina State University alumni]]\n[[Category:American bankers]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of the United States to Barbados]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of the United States to Antigua and Barbuda]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of the United States to Dominica]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of the United States to Grenada]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of the United States to Saint Lucia]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of the United States to Saint Kitts and Nevis]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of the United States to Saint Vincent and the Grenadines]]\n[[Category:American women bankers]]\n[[Category:American company founders]]\n[[Category:American women diplomats]]\n\n\n{{US-gov-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Jeanette W. Hyde''' (born 1938) is an American diplomat. She was [[Ambassadors of the United States|Ambassador of the United States]] to [[Barbados]], [[Dominica]], [[St Lucia]] from 1994 to 1998, and to [[Antigua]], [[Grenada]], [[Saint Vincent and the Grenadines|St. Vincent]], and [[St. Christopher-Nevis-Anguilla]] from 1995 to 1998, under [[Bill Clinton]].<ref name=\"history\">[https://history.state.gov/departmenthistory/people/hyde-jeanette-w U.S. Department of State]</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nJeanette W. Hyde was born in 1938.<ref name=\"history\"/> She attended [[Wake Forest University]], and received a [[B.S.]] from [[Delta State University]] in 1962.<ref name=\"American Ambassadors\">[http://www.americanambassadors.org/index.cfm?fuseaction=Members.view&memberid=116 American Ambassadors] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070103082902/http://www.americanambassadors.org/index.cfm?fuseaction=Members.view&memberid=116 |date=2007-01-03 }}</ref> She later attended the [[University of Maryland]] on their [[Iraklion, Crete]] campus, and competed graduate studies in Counseling at the [[University of North Carolina, Chapel Hill]] and the [[North Carolina State University]].<ref name=\"American Ambassadors\"/> She was teaching school for two years in [[Crete]] before going into social work and counseling with the N.C. Administrative Office of the Courts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news-prod.wcu.edu/2005/03/wallace-hyde-gift-to-western-to-endow-social-work-professorship-in-wifes-honor/|title=Wallace Hyde gift to Western to endow social work professorship in wife's honor|date=2005-03-11|website=WCU News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref>\n\nShe married the late Wallace Hyde, a [[Robbinsville, North Carolina]] native, and was a longtime Democratic Party fundraiser.<ref>[http://projects.newsobserver.com/under_the_dome/wallace_hyde_the_democrats_big_guy_dies News & Observer: Wallace Hyde, the Democrats' big guy, dies]</ref>  \n\nShe co-founded two banks in [[Raleigh, North Carolina]], Triangle Bank and North State Bank.<ref name=\"American Ambassadors\"/>\n\nShe serves on the Board of Directors of the [[North Carolina Board of Transportation]], the [[Global TransPark|North Carolina Global Transpark]], the [[North Carolina International Trade Commission]], Outward Bound of North Carolina, and the North Carolina Child Advocacy Institute.<ref name=\"American Ambassadors\"/> She also serves on the Board of Trustees of [[Wake Forest University]], [[Western Carolina University]], and American Diplomacy Journal, Inc. She previously served on the Board of The International Cabinet at the [[University of North Carolina at Wilmington]], the Triangle World Affairs Council, Methodist Home for Children, the North Carolina Community Foundation and The Eisenhower Exchange Fellowship Board.<ref name=\"American Ambassadors\"/> \n\n== Awards ==\nIn 1994, Hyde was awared with the Outstanding Woman in Public Service Award by the YWCA Academy of Women.\n\nIn 1998, she received the Triangle World Affairs Council's Distinguished Citizen for Public Service Award and the International Visitors Council's Citizen of the World Award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news-prod.wcu.edu/2005/03/wallace-hyde-gift-to-western-to-endow-social-work-professorship-in-wifes-honor/|title=Wallace Hyde gift to Western to endow social work professorship in wife's honor|date=2005-03-11|website=WCU News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-dip}}\n{{s-bef|rows=7|before= [[G. Philip Hughes]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title = [[United States Ambassador to Barbados]]|years = 1994-1998}}\n{{s-aft|rows=7|after= [[E. William Crotty]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title= [[United States Ambassador to Dominica]]| years  = 1994-1998}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States Ambassador to Saint Lucia]]| years  = 1994-1998}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title= [[United States Ambassador to Saint Vincent and the Grenadines]] | years  = 1994-1998}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title= [[United States Ambassador to Antigua and Barbuda]]| years  = 1995-1998}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States Ambassador to Grenada]]| years = 1995-1998}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title= [[United States Ambassador to Saint Kitts and Nevis]]| years  =  1995-1998}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hyde, Jeanette W.}}\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Wake Forest University alumni]]\n[[Category:Delta State University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Maryland, College Park alumni]]\n[[Category:University of North Carolina at Chapel Hi